    "narrative": "The daily efficiency audit for Ghost Ride the WHIP highlights **Mickey Moniak** (75.98) and **Jazz Chisholm Jr.** (74.79) as our cornerstone starts for today's slate. **Mickey Moniak** benefits from a massive 14% park factor boost and favorable dynamic platoon splits against Mike Burrows, allowing him to capitalize on his #2 order slot. Similarly, **Jazz Chisholm Jr.** remains a high-floor play against Civale; despite the minor drag from an elite-armed catcher, his base efficiency and park-adjusted ceiling make him an essential anchor in the middle of our order. While **Corbin Carroll** faces a tougher test against Peralta, his ability to exploit the pitcher\u2019s slow delivery\u2014a critical factor given our prioritization of speed\u2014keeps his efficiency elevated at 67.08, confirming his status as an automatic start regardless of the SP_xERA.\n\nThe most challenging decision for today\u2019s construction was the exclusion of **Josh Naylor**, who finished just outside the starting cut at 50.44. While **Josh Naylor** offers consistent power, the combination of Eovaldi\u2019s elite 3.17 xERA and the higher efficiency profiles of our existing infield\u2014specifically **Vinnie Pasquantino** (69.46) and **Austin Riley** (61.00)\u2014pushed him to the bench to preserve our game caps. **Vinnie Pasquantino** remains a strong play today, fueled by a 14% platoon edge and a favorable matchup against Williams. We are tracking the lineup status for **Austin Riley** closely; if he is not confirmed in the #4 hole, we may need to re-evaluate his marginal utility compared to the depth options currently held in reserve, such as **Max Muncy**.\n\nRisks remain, particularly concerning **Gabriel Moreno**, whose efficiency score of 49.97 sits right on the borderline of our rotation threshold. His matchup against the dangerous Peralta, combined with a negative park adjustment, makes him our most volatile start. Conversely, the matchups against Civale serve as the primary engine for our offensive output today. We have favorable projections for **Giancarlo Stanton** (63.57) and **Jose Caballero** (53.75) in that same game, though **Jose Caballero**'s value is suppressed by his #9 spot in the lineup. Our overall strategy remains focused on maximizing these platoon-heavy edges to offset the difficulty of facing pitchers like Peralta and Misiorowski.",
